<div id="review_3829681449" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3829681449" />
    <a title="Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10298127-anne"><img alt="Anne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530315692p2/10298127.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3829681449?book_show_action=true">Feb 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne" href="/user/show/10298127-anne">Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781782119074" href="/book/show/31344309-hope-in-the-dark">review of another edition</a>

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10298127-anne?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3829681449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8445902566799750536"><i>Hope in the Dark</i> is a necessary book for anyone who is overwhelmed by the many injustices, crises, and disasters in this world, for anyone who feels themselves growing increasingly despondent in the face of all this. <br/><br/>It is a book which aims to correct common misconceptions about activism, and Rebecca Solnit convincingly shows that there are many: for example, how protests come into being, how they work, and what constitutes a success. She is uninterested in easy binaries such as optimism and pes</span>
  <span id="freeText8445902566799750536" style="display:none"><i>Hope in the Dark</i> is a necessary book for anyone who is overwhelmed by the many injustices, crises, and disasters in this world, for anyone who feels themselves growing increasingly despondent in the face of all this. <br /><br />It is a book which aims to correct common misconceptions about activism, and Rebecca Solnit convincingly shows that there are many: for example, how protests come into being, how they work, and what constitutes a success. She is uninterested in easy binaries such as optimism and pessimism, because they condense complex issues to something more simple and less true, and because both prevent action when action is highly needed. In this text as in every other I've read by her, Solnit is critical, insightful, and practical.<br /><br />This dual structure - giving many examples of successful activism and its myriad effects on the one hand, and unravelling the narrative of what is successful activism in the first place - makes for a very convincing, and dare I say it, hopeful text. This text implies that you may be wrong about the future, and about what you think is possible - and that being wrong can be a great thing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8445902566799750536" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


